    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1108">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111Un3/8</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                    <gloss type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 142]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 8, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 9</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honour to acknowledge your note No.
                    733 of April 5, received to-day, informing me that complaint has been made to
                    your Department concerning the frequent appearance on the streets of Detroit of
                    uniformed Canadian soldiers wearing filled cartridge belts. You ask that the
                    attention of the Canadian Government may be called to the matter and express the
                    hope that instructions may be issued to prevent a continuance of the
                    practice.</p>
                <p>I have the honour to inform you in reply that I am at once bringing the matter to
                    the notice of the Canadian Government.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
